{"title_page": "Earl Wood", "text_new": "{{for|the school superintendent in Maryland|Earle B. Wood}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Earl H. Wood\n| image = EarlHWood.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Earl Wood in his office at the Mayo Clinic with an inset photo from 1946 showing him in Heidelberg, as part of [[operation paperclip]], seeking to recruit German scientists to work in the United States.\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1912|1|1|df=y}}<ref>''[http://people.mnhs.org/finder/bci/1912-02464 Minnesota, Birth Index, 1900-1934]''</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Mankato]], [[Minnesota]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2009|3|18|1912|1|1|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Rochester, Minnesota]]\n| citizenship = United States\n| nationality = United States\n| alma_mater = [[Macalester College]]<br />[[University of Minnesota]]\n| thesis_title = The Distribution of Electrolytes and Water Between Cardiac Muscle and Blood Serum with Special Reference to the Effects of Digitalis\n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = 1942\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for = Invention of the G-suit, Development of cardiac catheterization into a clinical service, Invention of the ear oximeter, Co-inventor of the first dynamic (high speed) volumetric x-ray computed tomography system\n| influences = Aerospace Physiology, Cardiovascular Monitoring, Cardiovascular Dynamics, Medical Instrumentation\n| influenced = \n| awards = Presidential Certificate of Merit from Harry Truman-1947; Macalester College honorary degree of D.Sc.-1950; American Heart Association's \"Career Investigator\" 1962; Distinguished Citizen Award-1974; honorary member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences-1977; honorary member American College of Cardiology - 1978; honorary degree, doctor of medicine, from the University of Bern, Switzerland - 1978; Humboldt Prize for Senior U.S. Scientists by the government of West Germany - 1979; John Phillips Memorial Award of the American College of Physicians - 1979; President of the American Physiological Society - 1980-81; President of the Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology (FASEB) - 1981-82; John Phillips Memorial Award of the American College of Physicians 1982; Aerospace Medical Association's Lyster Award for outstanding achievement in Aerospace medicine 1983; Ray G. Daggs Award for his distinguished long-term service to the science of physiology and, in particular, to the American Physiological Society - 1995; Street in Rheinfelden, Germany dedicated as \"Earl H. Wood Strasse\" - 2002.\n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| ethnicity = \n| field = Cardiovascular, Respiratory, Aerospace Medicine and Cardiovascular and Pulmonary Dynamics\n| work_institutions = Mayo Clinic<br />Rochester, Minnesota\n| religion = \n}}\n\n'''Earl Howard Wood''' (January 1, 1912 &ndash; March 18, 2009) was an American cardiopulmonary physiologist who helped invent the [[G-suit]], brought heart catheterization into a clinical reality and introduced dynamic volumetric computed tomography for the study of the heart and lungs.<ref name=NYTObit>{{cite news|title=Earl H. Wood Is Dead at 97; Helped Invent G-Suit|first=Jeremy|last=Pearce|date=March 26, 2009|accessdate=March 27, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/27/us/27wood.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123819290677361041|title=A Research Physician's Innovations Bore Fruit in Unexpected Ways|first=Stephen|last=Miller|date=28 March 2009|publisher=|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Ritman EL 1985 p 4\" />\n\n==Career==\n===[[G-Suit]]===\nShortly after receiving an [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] and [[PhD]] in physiology from the [[University of Minnesota]] medical school under the mentorship of Professor [[Maurice B. Visscher]], MD,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fox|first=JJ|title=Maurice B. Visscher at seventy-five--a life in the service of humanity|journal=Circ. Res.|date=September 1976|volume=39|issue=3 |pages=295\u2013296|pmid=782741|doi=10.1161/01.res.39.3.295}}</ref> Wood became a key member of a team, working in a, what was then top secret, laboratory at the [[Mayo Clinic]], tasked with helping military pilots and flight crew survive and function in high [[G-force]] environments. Based upon extensive physiologic testing via use of the human centrifuge installed at the Mayo Clinic, it was determined that blackout and then unconsciousness was caused by reduction of blood flow to the eyes first and then the brain.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Lambert|first2=EH|others=et al.|title=Effects of acceleration in relation to aviation|journal=Fed Proc.|date=September 1946|volume=5|pages=327\u2013344|pmid=20999477}}</ref> The solutions the team arrived at were the M-1 breath hold maneuver<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wood | first1 = EH | year = 1947 | title = Use of the Valsalva maneuver to increase man's tolerance to positive acceleration | url = | journal = Fed Proc. | volume = 6 | issue = | page = 229 | pmid = 20342926 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wood | first1 = EH | last2 = Hallenbeck | first2 = GA | year = 1946 | title = Voluntary (self-protective) maneuvers which can be used to increase man's tolerance to positive acceleration | url = | journal = Fed Proc. | volume = 5 | issue = | page = 115 | pmid = 21066535 }}</ref> and the [[G-suit]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wood | first1 = EH | last2 = Lambert | first2 = EH | year = 1946 | title = The effect of anti-blackout suits on blood pressure changes produced on the human centrifuge | url = | journal = Fed Proc. | volume = 5 | issue = | page = 115 | pmid = 21066536 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Lambert | first1 = EH | last2 = Wood | first2 = EH | date = Jul 1946 | title = The problem of blackout and unconsciousness in aviators | url = | journal = Med Clin North Am. | volume = 30 | issue = 4| pages = 833\u201344 | pmid = 20992942 }}</ref> The M-1 maneuver consisted of a strained exhalation effort against a closed glottis designed to increase left ventricular pressure. The G suit was a garment, produced by the [[David Clark Company]], which has air bladders situated at the calves, thighs, and abdomen of the wearer. The bladders inflate as the G-force acting on the aircraft increase, constricting the wearer's arteries, hence increasing blood pressure and blood flow to the brain.\n\nThe G-suit was a superior solution to another alternative (a water-filled suit) being tested at the time, which was considered impractically heavy and cumbersome. The water-filled, pulsatile pressure suits were developed to effect venous return.  However, Wood and colleagues' detailed physiologic measurements demonstrated that what was required was augmentation of arterial pressure.\n\nWood himself regularly tested the flight suits, taking many turns in a human centrifuge and plane dubbed the \"G-wiz.\" He calculated that over his several hundred rides, he had lost consciousness for an aggregate of at least fifteen minutes (without any observed lasting damage). Wood was awarded a Presidential Certificate of Merit by Harry Truman in 1947.\n\nThe G-suit was adopted in the 1940s. The current models are based on the pattern Wood and his colleagues designed. Following World War II, Wood was recruited to participate in what was known as \"[[Operation Paperclip]]\"<ref name=Hansel>{{cite web|url=http://www.postbulletin.com/inside-inventor-had-a-life-outside-of-science/article_533fb0fc-43f2-5699-af8e-4c5280a741a6.html|title=INSIDE Inventor had a life outside of science|work=[[Post-Bulletin]]|date=27 October 2008|first=Jeff|last=Hansel}}</ref> The goal was to keep the top German scientists away from Russia and working for the United States.\n\nIn 1962, Wood was the tenth scientist to be named \"Career Investigator,\" of the American Heart Association.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal | last1 = Burchell | first1 = HB | last2 = Wood | first2 = Earl H. | date = May 1987 | title = outstanding twentieth century investigator of the heart and circulation | url = | journal = Clin Cardiol | volume = 10 | issue = 5| pages = 372\u20134 | pmid = 3297443 | doi=10.1002/clc.4960100518}}</ref> These funds allowed Wood considerable flexibility in regards to the directions of his research.\n\n=== Other work ===\nAfter his work on the G-Suit, Wood worked on techniques for measuring cardiac blood flow. He was granted a [[patent]] for the ear oximeter, an optical instrument that measures blood oxygen levels without taking blood by examining the variation of light absorption as a function of oxygen saturation of hemoglobin. Integral to the work leading to the development of the G suit was the perfection of vascular catheterization methods needed to understand the distribution of blood pressure and flow.  Shortly after the end of World War II, open-heart surgery emerged with the Mayo contribution<ref name=Kirklin>{{cite journal|last1=Kirklin|first1=JW|last2=Dushane|first2=JW|last3=Patrick|first3=RT|last4=Donald|first4=DE|last5=Hetzel|first5=PS|last6=Harshbarger|first6=HG|last7=Wood|first7=EH|title=Intracardiac surgery with the aid of a mechanical pump-oxygenator system (gibbon type): report of eight cases|journal=Proc Staff Meet Mayo Clin|date=May 18, 1955|volume=30|number=10|pages=201\u2013206|pmid=14371757}}</ref> to the development of the heart-lung bypass machine initially developed by Gibbons<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stokes|first1=TL|last2=Gibbon|first2=JH Jr.|title=Experimental maintenance of life by a mechanical heart and lung during occlusion of the venae cavae followed by survival |journal=Surgery, gynecology & obstetrics|date=August 1950|volume=91|issue=2|pages=138\u2013156|pmid=15442833}}</ref> and perfected by Wood and colleagues.<ref name=Kirklin/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Gibbon|first=JH|title=Application of a mechanical heart and lung apparatus to cardiac surgery|journal=Minn Med|volume=37|issue=3|pages=171\u2013185|year=1954|pmid=13154149}}</ref> Wood's work at the Mayo Clinic lead to the development of many technologies<ref name=\"Ritman EL 1985 p 4\"/> allowing for the assessment of the heart and lungs including dye dilution methods serving to characterize cardiac output,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last1=Grace|first=JB|last2=Fox|first2=IJ|last3=Crowley|first3=WP Jr|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Thoracic-aorta flow in man|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=November 1957|volume=11|number=3|pages=405\u2013418|pmid=13480951|doi=10.1152/jappl.1957.11.3.405}}</ref> methods for the assessment of central blood volume,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bowers|first1=D|last2=Shepherd|first2=JT|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=A constant-rate indicator-infusion technic for the measurement of central vascular volume in man|journal=Can J Biochem Physiol|date=May 1955|volume=33|number=3|pages=340\u2013348|pmid=14364323|doi=10.1139/o55-045}}</ref> the calculation of [[vascular resistance|pulmonary vascular resistance]] (known as the \"Wood Unit\" and calculated by subtracting pulmonary capillary wedge pressure from the mean pulmonary arterial pressure and dividing by the cardiac output),<ref name=Connolly1954/><ref name=Swan1959/><ref name=Shepherd1959/> analog subtraction angiography, and eventually the Dynamic Spatial Reconstructor (DSR), a predecessor to modern high speed volumetric [[computed tomography]] (CT) allowing for the evaluation of the beating heart and breathing lungs.  The DSR comprised 14 X-ray tubes and a hemicylindrical fluorescent screen imaged by 14 associated television cameras.<ref>Ritman EL, Kinsey JH, Robb RA, Gilbert BK, Harris LD, Wood EH. Three-dimensional imaging of heart, lungs, and circulation. Science. 1980 Oct 17;210(4467):273-80. PubMed {{PMID|7423187}}.</ref><ref>Robb RA, Sinak LJ, Hoffman EA, Kinsey JH, Harris LD, Ritman EL. Dynamic volume imaging of moving organs. J Med Syst. 1982 Dec;6(6):539-54. PubMed {{PMID|7183727}}.</ref>\n\nIn all, Wood is noted for his contributions (together with members of the Biodynamics Research Unit (BRU), under his direction, within the Physiology and Biophysics Department at the [[Mayo Clinic]]) in the following areas:\n* methods for protection against blackout and unconsciousness during high G-forces<ref>Wood EH. Contributions of aeromedical research to flight and biomedical science\" ''Aviat Space Environ Med'' 1986 Oct;57(10 Pt 2):A13-23. Erratum in: Aviat Space Environ Med 1987 Jul;58(7):706. PubMed {{PMID|3778400}}.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wood | first1 = EH | date = Jul 1987 | title = Development of anti-G suits and their limitations | url = | journal = Aviat Space Environ Med | volume = 58 | issue = 7| pages = 699\u2013706 | pmid = 3304268 }}</ref><ref>Wood EH. \"Development of methods for prevention of acceleration induced blackout and unconsciousness in World War II fighter pilots. Limitations: present and future. ''Physiologist.'' 1987 Feb;30(1 Suppl):S27-30. {{PMID|3550843}}.</ref>\n* methods for [[heart catheterization]]s;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burchell|first1=HB|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=Remarks on the technic and diagnostic applications of cardiac catheterization|journal=Proc Staff Meet Mayo Clin|date=February 1, 1950|volume=25|number=3|pages=41\u201348|pmid=15404372}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burchell|first1=HB|last2=Helmholz Jr.|first2=HF|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Over-all experiences with cardiac catheterization|journal=Proc Staff Meet Mayo Clin|date=February 11, 1953|volume=28|number=3|pages=50\u201357|pmid=13014125}}</ref>\n* methods for monitoring vascular pressures;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ellis|first=EJ|last2=Gauer|first2=OH|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=An intracardiac manometer: its evaluation and application|journal=Circulation|date=March 1951|volume=3|number=3|pages=390\u2013398|pmid=14812668|doi=10.1161/01.cir.3.3.390}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Leusen|first2=IR|last3=Warner|first3=HR|last4=Wright|first4=JL|title=Measurement of pressures in man by cardiac catheters|journal=Circ Res|date=July 1954|volume=2|number=4|pages=294\u2013303|pmid=13172871|doi=10.1161/01.res.2.4.294}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wood | first1 = EH | date = Sep 1978 | title = Evolution of instrumentation and techniques for the study of cardiovascular dynamics from the Thirties to 1980, Alza lecture, April 10, 1978 | url = | journal = Ann. Biomed. Eng. | volume = 6 | issue = 3| pages = 250\u2013309 | pmid = 367231 | doi=10.1007/bf02409346}}</ref>\n* the [[pulse oximeter]] for real time non-invasive monitoring or arterial oxygen saturation;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Geraci|first2=JE|last3=Groom|first3=DL|title=Photoelectric determination of blood oxygen saturation in man|journal=Fed Proc|date=March 1948|volume=7|issue=1 Pt 1 |page=137|pmid=18934670}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Geraci|first2=JE|title=Photoelectric determination of arterial oxygen saturation in man|journal=J Lab Clin Med|date=March 1949|volume=34|number=3|pages=387\u2013401|pmid=18113925}}</ref>\n* methods for calculation of [[vascular resistance|pulmonary vascular resistance]] (Wood Unit);<ref name=Connolly1954>{{cite journal|last1=Connolly|first1=DC|last2=Kirklin|first2=JW|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=The relationship between pulmonary artery wedge pressure and left atrial pressure in man|journal=Circ. Res.|date=September 1954|volume=2|number=5|pages=434\u2013440|pmid=13190627|doi=10.1161/01.res.2.5.434}}</ref><ref name=Swan1959>{{cite journal|last1=Swan|first1=HJ|last2=Burchell|first2=HB|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Effect of oxygen on pulmonary vascular resistance in patients with pulmonary hypertension associated with atrial septal defect|journal=Circulation|date=July 1959|volume=20|number=1|pages=66\u201373|pmid=13663195|doi=10.1161/01.cir.20.1.66}}</ref><ref name=Shepherd1959>{{cite journal|last1=Shepherd|first1=JT|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=The role of vessel tone in pulmonary hypertension|journal=Circulation|date=May 1959|volume=19|number=5|pages=641\u2013645|pmid=13652355|doi=10.1161/01.cir.19.5.641}}</ref>\n* methods for the digital conversion of analog physiologic signals allowing for computer-based monitoring of vascular signals (using the early computer developments of IBM which was just down the road from Wood\u2019s laboratory);<ref name=\"Ritman EL 1985 p 4\">{{cite journal|last=Ritman|first=EL|title=Earl Wood--a research career noted for development of novel instruments driven by the power of the indicator dilution concept|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=November 1, 2014|volume=117|issue=9 |pages=945\u2013956|doi=10.1152/japplphysiol.00491.2014|pmid=25190740}}</ref>\n* methods for [[liquid breathing|liquid fluorocarbon respiration]] explored for protection against high G forces expected during rocket launch and re-entry while leaving and returning to earth\u2019s atmosphere in space exploration;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sass|first1=DJ|last2=Ritman|first2=EL|last3=Caskey|first3=PE|last4=Banchero|first4=N|last5=Wood|first5=EH|title=Liquid breathing: prevention of pulmonary arterial-venous shunting during acceleration|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=April 1972|volume=32|number=4|pages=451\u2013455|pmid=4503080}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sass|first1=DJ|last2=Nolan|first2=AC|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Digital computer analysis of circulatory and respiratory pressures in water-immersed dogs breathing liquid in force environments of 1 and 7 G|journal=Aerosp. Med.|date=January 1974|volume=45|number=1|pages=1\u201311|pmid=4521228}}</ref> \n* methods for the assessment of pleural pressure to determine regional gravitational effects on the lung;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Banchero|first1=N|last2=Schwartz|first2=PE|last3=Tsakiris|first3=AG|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Pleural and esophageal pressures in the upright body position|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=August 1967|volume=23|number=2|pages=228\u2013234|pmid=6031193}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rutishauser|first1=WJ|last2=Banchero|first2=N|last3=Tsakiris|first3=AG|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Effect of gravitational and inertial forces on pleural and esophageal pressures|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=June 1967|volume=22|number=6|pages=1041\u20131052|pmid=6027051}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rutishauser|first1=WJ|last2=Banchero|first2=N|last3=Tsakiris|first3=AG|last4=Edmundowicz|first4=AC|last5=Wood|first5=EH|title=Pleural pressures at dorsal and ventral sites in supine and prone body positions|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=September 1966|volume=21|number=5|pages=1500\u20131510|pmid=5923220|doi=10.1152/jappl.1966.21.5.1500}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hoffman|first1=EA|last2=Behrenbeck|first2=T|last3=Chevalier|first3=PA|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Estimation of regional pleural surface expansile forces in intact dogs|journal=J Appl Physiol Respir Environ Exerc Physiol|date=September 1983|volume=55|number=3|pages=935\u2013948|pmid=6355027}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hoffman|first1=EA|last2=Ritman|first2=EL|title=Heart-lung interaction: effect on regional lung air content and total heart volume|journal=Ann. Biomed. Eng.|year=1987|volume=15|number=3-4|pages=241\u2013257|pmid=3662146|doi=10.1007/bf02584282}}</ref> \n* indicator dilution curve methodology for the assessment of cardiac output and other physiologic derivative;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Warner|first1=HR|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=Simplified calculation of cardiac output from dye dilution curves recorded by oximeter|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=September 1952|volume=5|number=3|pages=111\u2013116|pmid=12990551|doi=10.1152/jappl.1952.5.3.111}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shepherd|first1=JT|last2=Bowers|first2=D|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Measurement of cardiac output in man by injection of dye at a constant rate into the right ventricle or pulmonary artery|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=May 1955|volume=7|number=6|pages=629\u2013638|pmid=14381340|doi=10.1152/jappl.1955.7.6.629}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hetzel|first1=P|last2=Swan|first2=HJ|last3=Ramirez de Arellano|first3=AA|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Estimation of cardiac output from first part of arterial dye-dilution curves|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=July 1958|volume=13|number=1|pages=92\u201396|pmid=13563349}}</ref>\n* [[indocyanine green]] dye for use in the indicator dilution method;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fox|first1=IJ|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=Indocyanine green: physical and physiologic properties|journal=Proc Staff Meet Mayo Clin|date=December 7, 1960|volume=35|pages=732\u2013744|pmid=13701100}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Edwards|first1=AW|last2=Isaacson|first2=J|last3=Sutterer|first3=WF|last4=Bassingthwaighte|first4=JB|last5=Wood|first5=EH|title=Indocyanine green densitometry in flowing blood compensated for background dye|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=November 1963|volume=18|pages=1294\u20131304|pmid=14080764|pmc=2997752|doi=10.1152/jappl.1963.18.6.1294}}</ref> \n* analog subtraction [[angiography]] for the assessment of cardiac structures via video [[fluoroscopy]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=JC|last2=Sturm|first2=RE|last3=Tsakiris|first3=AG|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Biplane videoangiography|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=May 1968|volume=24|number=5|pages=724\u2013727|pmid=5647655|doi=10.1152/jappl.1968.24.5.724}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sturm|first1=RE|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=The video quantizer: an electronic photometer to measure contrast in roentgen fluoroscopic images|journal=Mayo Clin. Proc.|date=November 1968|volume=43|number=11|pages=803\u2013806|pmid=5711440}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Greenleaf|first1=JF|last2=Ritman|first2=EL|last3=Wood|first3=EH|last4=Robb|first4=RA|last5=Johnson|first5=SA|title=Dynamic computer-generated displays of data from biplane roentgen angiography for study of the left ventricle|journal=Ann. Biomed. Eng.|date=March 1974|volume=2|number=1|pages=90\u2013105|pmid=4596338|doi=10.1007/bf02368088}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=HC|last2=Sturm|first2=RE|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Videodensitometric system for measurement of vessel blood flow, particularly in the coronary arteries, in man|journal=Am J Cardiol|date=August 1973|volume=32|number=2|pages=144\u2013150|pmid=4578631|doi=10.1016/s0002-9149(73)80112-2}}</ref> and \n* the earliest predecessor (The Dynamic Spatial Reconstructor)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Ritman|first2=EL|last3=Robb|first3=RA|last4=Harris|first4=LD|last5=Ruegsegger|first5=P|title=Noninvasive numerical vivisection of anatomic structure and function of the intact circulatory system using high temporal resolution cylindrical scanning computerized tomography|journal=Med. Instrum.|date=May 1977|volume=11|number=3|pages=153\u2013159|pmid=875764}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Johnson|first1=SA|last2=Robb|first2=RA|last3=Greenleaf|first3=JF|last4=Ritman|first4=EL|last5=Lee|first5=SL|last6=Herman|first6=GT|last7=Sturm|first7=RE|last8=Wood|first8=EH|title=The problem of accurate measurement of left ventricular shape and dimensions from multiplane roentgenographic data|journal=Eur J Cardiol.|date=March 1974|volume=1|number=3|pages=241\u2013258|pmid=4613557}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Wood|first=EH|title=The dream of a dynamic, high-fidelity, synchronous, volumetric imaging system and the road to its realization|journal=Herz|date=August 1985|volume=10|issue=4 |pages=183\u2013192|pmid=3899883}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ritman|first1=EL|last2=Robb|first2=RA|last3=Harris|first3=LD|title=Imaging Physiological Functions: Experience with the Dynamic Spatial Reconstructor|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=1985|isbn=0030693527}}</ref> of modern high speed, multi-source / multi-detector row computed tomography for the non-invasive imaging of the beating heart and breathing lungs.\n\nWood's publication list, with more than 700 entries, is a testament to the number of fellows who trained under him and who became prominent researchers in their own right.\n\n== Early life ==\nEarl Wood was born to Inez Goff and William Clark Wood in Mankato, Minnesota on January 1, 1912 and started life on a subsistence farm.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite AV media|title=Inventing the G-suit: The Life Story of Dr. Earl Wood|first1=Bill|last1=Bonde|first2=Karen|last2=Bonde|url=https://vimeo.com/1924164}}</ref>  William Wood, in addition to farming, was a real estate businessman. Earl Wood earned a B.A. in Mathematics and Chemistry from Macalester College in 1934, and his MD degree and a PhD degree in physiology from the University of Minnesota. Earl was one of 5 brothers (Earl, Chester, Delbert, Harland and Abe) and a sister, Louise.\n\n== Family ==\nAll of Earl Wood's siblings grew up to be highly accomplished.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Louise A. Wood was awarded the [[Medal of Freedom (1945)|Medal of Freedom]] by President Truman for her services as over-seas director of the American Red Cross during World War II. and became the executive director of the [[Girl Scouts of the USA]] from 1961-1972. [[Harland G. Wood]] was the first director of the Department of Biochemistry at the School of Medicine and Dean of Sciences, Case Western Reserve University. As a biochemist, he was notable for proving in 1935 that animals, humans and bacteria utilized carbon dioxide<ref>Wood HG, Utter MF. The role of CO2 fixation in metabolism. Essays Biochem. 1965;1:1-27. Review. PubMed {{PMID|4880809}}.</ref> and received the National Medal of Science. Chester was a teacher and a university administrator; Delbert was, in succession, a lawyer, a Federal Bureau of Investigation agent, and a railway executive; Abe was an internist and founder of a Colorado-based medical clinic. Not surprisingly, in 1950, Earl Wood's mother, Inez, was awarded the title of \"Minnesota Mother of the Year.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>  Earl and his wife, Ada, had a daughter, Phoebe and three sons, Mark, Guy and E. Andrew.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, Earl H.}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:American physiologists]]\n[[Category:American medical researchers]]\n[[Category:Cardiovascular researchers]]\n[[Category:American biomedical engineers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the school superintendent in Maryland|Earle B. Wood}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Earl H. Wood\n| image = EarlHWood.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Earl Wood in his office at the Mayo Clinic with an inset photo from 1946 showing him in Heidelberg, as part of [[operation paperclip]], seeking to recruit German scientists to work in the United States.\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1912|1|1|df=y}}<ref>''[http://people.mnhs.org/finder/bci/1912-02464 Minnesota, Birth Index, 1900-1934]''</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Mankato]], [[Minnesota]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2009|3|18|1912|1|1|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Rochester, Minnesota]]\n| citizenship = United States\n| nationality = United States\n| alma_mater = [[Macalester College]]<br />[[University of Minnesota]]\n| thesis_title = The Distribution of Electrolytes and Water Between Cardiac Muscle and Blood Serum with Special Reference to the Effects of Digitalis\n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = 1942\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for = Invention of the G-suit, Development of cardiac catheterization into a clinical service, Invention of the ear oximeter, Co-inventor of the first dynamic (high speed) volumetric x-ray computed tomography system\n| influences = Aerospace Physiology, Cardiovascular Monitoring, Cardiovascular Dynamics, Medical Instrumentation\n| influenced = \n| awards = Presidential Certificate of Merit from Harry Truman-1947; Macalester College honorary degree of D.Sc.-1950; American Heart Association's \"Career Investigator\" 1962; Distinguished Citizen Award-1974; honorary member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences-1977; honorary member American College of Cardiology - 1978; honorary degree, doctor of medicine, from the University of Bern, Switzerland - 1978; Humboldt Prize for Senior U.S. Scientists by the government of West Germany - 1979; John Phillips Memorial Award of the American College of Physicians - 1979; President of the American Physiological Society - 1980-81; President of the Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology (FASEB) - 1981-82; John Phillips Memorial Award of the American College of Physicians 1982; Aerospace Medical Association's Lyster Award for outstanding achievement in Aerospace medicine 1983; Ray G. Daggs Award for his distinguished long-term service to the science of physiology and, in particular, to the American Physiological Society - 1995; Street in Rheinfelden, Germany dedicated as \"Earl H. Wood Strasse\" - 2002.\n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| ethnicity = \n| field = Cardiovascular, Respiratory, Aerospace Medicine and Cardiovascular and Pulmonary Dynamics\n| work_institutions = Mayo Clinic<br />Rochester, Minnesota\n| religion = \n}}\n\n'''Earl Howard Wood''' (January 1, 1912 &ndash; March 18, 2009) was an American cardiopulmonary physiologist who helped invent the [[G-suit]], brought heart catheterization into a clinical reality and introduced dynamic volumetric computed tomography for the study of the heart and lungs.<ref name=NYTObit>{{cite news|title=Earl H. Wood Is Dead at 97; Helped Invent G-Suit|first=Jeremy|last=Pearce|date=March 26, 2009|accessdate=March 27, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/27/us/27wood.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123819290677361041|title=A Research Physician's Innovations Bore Fruit in Unexpected Ways|first=Stephen|last=Miller|date=28 March 2009|publisher=|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Ritman EL 1985 p 4\" />\n\n==Career==\n===[[G-Suit]]===\nShortly after receiving an [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] and [[PhD]] in physiology from the [[University of Minnesota]] medical school under the mentorship of Professor [[Maurice B. Visscher]], MD,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fox|first=JJ|title=Maurice B. Visscher at seventy-five--a life in the service of humanity|journal=Circ. Res.|date=September 1976|volume=39|issue=3 |pages=295\u2013296|pmid=782741|doi=10.1161/01.res.39.3.295}}</ref> Wood became a key member of a team, working in a, what was then top secret, laboratory at the [[Mayo Clinic]], tasked with helping military pilots and flight crew survive and function in high [[G-force]] environments. Based upon extensive physiologic testing via use of the human centrifuge installed at the Mayo Clinic, it was determined that blackout and then unconsciousness was caused by reduction of blood flow to the eyes first and then the brain.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Lambert|first2=EH|others=et al.|title=Effects of acceleration in relation to aviation|journal=Fed Proc.|date=September 1946|volume=5|pages=327\u2013344|pmid=20999477}}</ref> The solutions the team arrived at were the M-1 breath hold maneuver<ref>WOOD EH. Use of the Valsalva maneuver to increase man's tolerance to positive acceleration. Fed Proc. 1947;6(1 Pt 2):229. PubMed {{PMID|20342926}}.</ref><ref>WOOD EH, HALLENBECK GA. Voluntary (self-protective) maneuvers which can be used to increase man's tolerance to positive acceleration. Fed Proc. 1946;5(1 Pt 2):115. PubMed {{PMID|21066535}}.</ref> and the [[G-suit]].<ref>WOOD EH, LAMBERT EH. The effect of anti-blackout suits on blood pressure changes produced on the human centrifuge. Fed Proc. 1946;5(1 Pt 2):115. PubMed {{PMID|21066536}}.</ref><ref>LAMBERT EH, WOOD EH. The problem of blackout and unconsciousness in aviators. Med Clin North Am. 1946 Jul;30(4):833-44. PubMed {{PMID|20992942}}.</ref> The M-1 maneuver consisted of a strained exhalation effort against a closed glottis designed to increase left ventricular pressure. The G suit was a garment, produced by the [[David Clark Company]], which has air bladders situated at the calves, thighs, and abdomen of the wearer. The bladders inflate as the G-force acting on the aircraft increase, constricting the wearer's arteries, hence increasing blood pressure and blood flow to the brain.\n\nThe G-suit was a superior solution to another alternative (a water-filled suit) being tested at the time, which was considered impractically heavy and cumbersome. The water-filled, pulsatile pressure suits were developed to effect venous return.  However, Wood and colleagues' detailed physiologic measurements demonstrated that what was required was augmentation of arterial pressure.\n\nWood himself regularly tested the flight suits, taking many turns in a human centrifuge and plane dubbed the \"G-wiz.\" He calculated that over his several hundred rides, he had lost consciousness for an aggregate of at least fifteen minutes (without any observed lasting damage). Wood was awarded a Presidential Certificate of Merit by Harry Truman in 1947.\n\nThe G-suit was adopted in the 1940s. The current models are based on the pattern Wood and his colleagues designed. Following World War II, Wood was recruited to participate in what was known as \"[[Operation Paperclip]]\"<ref name=Hansel>{{cite web|url=http://www.postbulletin.com/inside-inventor-had-a-life-outside-of-science/article_533fb0fc-43f2-5699-af8e-4c5280a741a6.html|title=INSIDE Inventor had a life outside of science|work=[[Post-Bulletin]]|date=27 October 2008|first=Jeff|last=Hansel}}</ref> The goal was to keep the top German scientists away from Russia and working for the United States.\n\nIn 1962, Wood was the tenth scientist to be named \"Career Investigator,\" of the American Heart Association.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal | last1 = Burchell | first1 = HB | last2 = Wood | first2 = Earl H. | date = May 1987 | title = outstanding twentieth century investigator of the heart and circulation | url = | journal = Clin Cardiol | volume = 10 | issue = 5| pages = 372\u20134 | pmid = 3297443 | doi=10.1002/clc.4960100518}}</ref> These funds allowed Wood considerable flexibility in regards to the directions of his research.\n\n=== Other work ===\nAfter his work on the G-Suit, Wood worked on techniques for measuring cardiac blood flow. He was granted a [[patent]] for the ear oximeter, an optical instrument that measures blood oxygen levels without taking blood by examining the variation of light absorption as a function of oxygen saturation of hemoglobin. Integral to the work leading to the development of the G suit was the perfection of vascular catheterization methods needed to understand the distribution of blood pressure and flow.  Shortly after the end of World War II, open-heart surgery emerged with the Mayo contribution<ref name=Kirklin>{{cite journal|last1=Kirklin|first1=JW|last2=Dushane|first2=JW|last3=Patrick|first3=RT|last4=Donald|first4=DE|last5=Hetzel|first5=PS|last6=Harshbarger|first6=HG|last7=Wood|first7=EH|title=Intracardiac surgery with the aid of a mechanical pump-oxygenator system (gibbon type): report of eight cases|journal=Proc Staff Meet Mayo Clin|date=May 18, 1955|volume=30|number=10|pages=201\u2013206|pmid=14371757}}</ref> to the development of the heart-lung bypass machine initially developed by Gibbons<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stokes|first1=TL|last2=Gibbon|first2=JH Jr.|title=Experimental maintenance of life by a mechanical heart and lung during occlusion of the venae cavae followed by survival |journal=Surgery, gynecology & obstetrics|date=August 1950|volume=91|issue=2|pages=138\u2013156|pmid=15442833}}</ref> and perfected by Wood and colleagues.<ref name=Kirklin/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Gibbon|first=JH|title=Application of a mechanical heart and lung apparatus to cardiac surgery|journal=Minn Med|volume=37|issue=3|pages=171\u2013185|year=1954|pmid=13154149}}</ref> Wood's work at the Mayo Clinic lead to the development of many technologies<ref name=\"Ritman EL 1985 p 4\"/> allowing for the assessment of the heart and lungs including dye dilution methods serving to characterize cardiac output,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last1=Grace|first=JB|last2=Fox|first2=IJ|last3=Crowley|first3=WP Jr|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Thoracic-aorta flow in man|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=November 1957|volume=11|number=3|pages=405\u2013418|pmid=13480951|doi=10.1152/jappl.1957.11.3.405}}</ref> methods for the assessment of central blood volume,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bowers|first1=D|last2=Shepherd|first2=JT|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=A constant-rate indicator-infusion technic for the measurement of central vascular volume in man|journal=Can J Biochem Physiol|date=May 1955|volume=33|number=3|pages=340\u2013348|pmid=14364323|doi=10.1139/o55-045}}</ref> the calculation of [[vascular resistance|pulmonary vascular resistance]] (known as the \"Wood Unit\" and calculated by subtracting pulmonary capillary wedge pressure from the mean pulmonary arterial pressure and dividing by the cardiac output),<ref name=Connolly1954/><ref name=Swan1959/><ref name=Shepherd1959/> analog subtraction angiography, and eventually the Dynamic Spatial Reconstructor (DSR), a predecessor to modern high speed volumetric [[computed tomography]] (CT) allowing for the evaluation of the beating heart and breathing lungs.  The DSR comprised 14 X-ray tubes and a hemicylindrical fluorescent screen imaged by 14 associated television cameras.<ref>Ritman EL, Kinsey JH, Robb RA, Gilbert BK, Harris LD, Wood EH. Three-dimensional imaging of heart, lungs, and circulation. Science. 1980 Oct 17;210(4467):273-80. PubMed {{PMID|7423187}}.</ref><ref>Robb RA, Sinak LJ, Hoffman EA, Kinsey JH, Harris LD, Ritman EL. Dynamic volume imaging of moving organs. J Med Syst. 1982 Dec;6(6):539-54. PubMed {{PMID|7183727}}.</ref>\n\nIn all, Wood is noted for his contributions (together with members of the Biodynamics Research Unit (BRU), under his direction, within the Physiology and Biophysics Department at the [[Mayo Clinic]]) in the following areas:\n* methods for protection against blackout and unconsciousness during high G-forces<ref>Wood EH. Contributions of aeromedical research to flight and biomedical science\" ''Aviat Space Environ Med'' 1986 Oct;57(10 Pt 2):A13-23. Erratum in: Aviat Space Environ Med 1987 Jul;58(7):706. PubMed {{PMID|3778400}}.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wood | first1 = EH | date = Jul 1987 | title = Development of anti-G suits and their limitations | url = | journal = Aviat Space Environ Med | volume = 58 | issue = 7| pages = 699\u2013706 | pmid = 3304268 }}</ref><ref>Wood EH. \"Development of methods for prevention of acceleration induced blackout and unconsciousness in World War II fighter pilots. Limitations: present and future. ''Physiologist.'' 1987 Feb;30(1 Suppl):S27-30. {{PMID|3550843}}.</ref>\n* methods for [[heart catheterization]]s;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burchell|first1=HB|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=Remarks on the technic and diagnostic applications of cardiac catheterization|journal=Proc Staff Meet Mayo Clin|date=February 1, 1950|volume=25|number=3|pages=41\u201348|pmid=15404372}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burchell|first1=HB|last2=Helmholz Jr.|first2=HF|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Over-all experiences with cardiac catheterization|journal=Proc Staff Meet Mayo Clin|date=February 11, 1953|volume=28|number=3|pages=50\u201357|pmid=13014125}}</ref>\n* methods for monitoring vascular pressures;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ellis|first=EJ|last2=Gauer|first2=OH|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=An intracardiac manometer: its evaluation and application|journal=Circulation|date=March 1951|volume=3|number=3|pages=390\u2013398|pmid=14812668|doi=10.1161/01.cir.3.3.390}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Leusen|first2=IR|last3=Warner|first3=HR|last4=Wright|first4=JL|title=Measurement of pressures in man by cardiac catheters|journal=Circ Res|date=July 1954|volume=2|number=4|pages=294\u2013303|pmid=13172871|doi=10.1161/01.res.2.4.294}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wood | first1 = EH | date = Sep 1978 | title = Evolution of instrumentation and techniques for the study of cardiovascular dynamics from the Thirties to 1980, Alza lecture, April 10, 1978 | url = | journal = Ann. Biomed. Eng. | volume = 6 | issue = 3| pages = 250\u2013309 | pmid = 367231 | doi=10.1007/bf02409346}}</ref>\n* the [[pulse oximeter]] for real time non-invasive monitoring or arterial oxygen saturation;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Geraci|first2=JE|last3=Groom|first3=DL|title=Photoelectric determination of blood oxygen saturation in man|journal=Fed Proc|date=March 1948|volume=7|issue=1 Pt 1 |page=137|pmid=18934670}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Geraci|first2=JE|title=Photoelectric determination of arterial oxygen saturation in man|journal=J Lab Clin Med|date=March 1949|volume=34|number=3|pages=387\u2013401|pmid=18113925}}</ref>\n* methods for calculation of [[vascular resistance|pulmonary vascular resistance]] (Wood Unit);<ref name=Connolly1954>{{cite journal|last1=Connolly|first1=DC|last2=Kirklin|first2=JW|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=The relationship between pulmonary artery wedge pressure and left atrial pressure in man|journal=Circ. Res.|date=September 1954|volume=2|number=5|pages=434\u2013440|pmid=13190627|doi=10.1161/01.res.2.5.434}}</ref><ref name=Swan1959>{{cite journal|last1=Swan|first1=HJ|last2=Burchell|first2=HB|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Effect of oxygen on pulmonary vascular resistance in patients with pulmonary hypertension associated with atrial septal defect|journal=Circulation|date=July 1959|volume=20|number=1|pages=66\u201373|pmid=13663195|doi=10.1161/01.cir.20.1.66}}</ref><ref name=Shepherd1959>{{cite journal|last1=Shepherd|first1=JT|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=The role of vessel tone in pulmonary hypertension|journal=Circulation|date=May 1959|volume=19|number=5|pages=641\u2013645|pmid=13652355|doi=10.1161/01.cir.19.5.641}}</ref>\n* methods for the digital conversion of analog physiologic signals allowing for computer-based monitoring of vascular signals (using the early computer developments of IBM which was just down the road from Wood\u2019s laboratory);<ref name=\"Ritman EL 1985 p 4\">{{cite journal|last=Ritman|first=EL|title=Earl Wood--a research career noted for development of novel instruments driven by the power of the indicator dilution concept|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=November 1, 2014|volume=117|issue=9 |pages=945\u2013956|doi=10.1152/japplphysiol.00491.2014|pmid=25190740}}</ref>\n* methods for [[liquid breathing|liquid fluorocarbon respiration]] explored for protection against high G forces expected during rocket launch and re-entry while leaving and returning to earth\u2019s atmosphere in space exploration;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sass|first1=DJ|last2=Ritman|first2=EL|last3=Caskey|first3=PE|last4=Banchero|first4=N|last5=Wood|first5=EH|title=Liquid breathing: prevention of pulmonary arterial-venous shunting during acceleration|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=April 1972|volume=32|number=4|pages=451\u2013455|pmid=4503080}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sass|first1=DJ|last2=Nolan|first2=AC|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Digital computer analysis of circulatory and respiratory pressures in water-immersed dogs breathing liquid in force environments of 1 and 7 G|journal=Aerosp. Med.|date=January 1974|volume=45|number=1|pages=1\u201311|pmid=4521228}}</ref> \n* methods for the assessment of pleural pressure to determine regional gravitational effects on the lung;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Banchero|first1=N|last2=Schwartz|first2=PE|last3=Tsakiris|first3=AG|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Pleural and esophageal pressures in the upright body position|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=August 1967|volume=23|number=2|pages=228\u2013234|pmid=6031193}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rutishauser|first1=WJ|last2=Banchero|first2=N|last3=Tsakiris|first3=AG|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Effect of gravitational and inertial forces on pleural and esophageal pressures|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=June 1967|volume=22|number=6|pages=1041\u20131052|pmid=6027051}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rutishauser|first1=WJ|last2=Banchero|first2=N|last3=Tsakiris|first3=AG|last4=Edmundowicz|first4=AC|last5=Wood|first5=EH|title=Pleural pressures at dorsal and ventral sites in supine and prone body positions|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=September 1966|volume=21|number=5|pages=1500\u20131510|pmid=5923220|doi=10.1152/jappl.1966.21.5.1500}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hoffman|first1=EA|last2=Behrenbeck|first2=T|last3=Chevalier|first3=PA|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Estimation of regional pleural surface expansile forces in intact dogs|journal=J Appl Physiol Respir Environ Exerc Physiol|date=September 1983|volume=55|number=3|pages=935\u2013948|pmid=6355027}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hoffman|first1=EA|last2=Ritman|first2=EL|title=Heart-lung interaction: effect on regional lung air content and total heart volume|journal=Ann. Biomed. Eng.|year=1987|volume=15|number=3-4|pages=241\u2013257|pmid=3662146|doi=10.1007/bf02584282}}</ref> \n* indicator dilution curve methodology for the assessment of cardiac output and other physiologic derivative;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Warner|first1=HR|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=Simplified calculation of cardiac output from dye dilution curves recorded by oximeter|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=September 1952|volume=5|number=3|pages=111\u2013116|pmid=12990551|doi=10.1152/jappl.1952.5.3.111}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shepherd|first1=JT|last2=Bowers|first2=D|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Measurement of cardiac output in man by injection of dye at a constant rate into the right ventricle or pulmonary artery|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=May 1955|volume=7|number=6|pages=629\u2013638|pmid=14381340|doi=10.1152/jappl.1955.7.6.629}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hetzel|first1=P|last2=Swan|first2=HJ|last3=Ramirez de Arellano|first3=AA|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Estimation of cardiac output from first part of arterial dye-dilution curves|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=July 1958|volume=13|number=1|pages=92\u201396|pmid=13563349}}</ref>\n* [[indocyanine green]] dye for use in the indicator dilution method;<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fox|first1=IJ|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=Indocyanine green: physical and physiologic properties|journal=Proc Staff Meet Mayo Clin|date=December 7, 1960|volume=35|pages=732\u2013744|pmid=13701100}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Edwards|first1=AW|last2=Isaacson|first2=J|last3=Sutterer|first3=WF|last4=Bassingthwaighte|first4=JB|last5=Wood|first5=EH|title=Indocyanine green densitometry in flowing blood compensated for background dye|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=November 1963|volume=18|pages=1294\u20131304|pmid=14080764|pmc=2997752|doi=10.1152/jappl.1963.18.6.1294}}</ref> \n* analog subtraction [[angiography]] for the assessment of cardiac structures via video [[fluoroscopy]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=JC|last2=Sturm|first2=RE|last3=Tsakiris|first3=AG|last4=Wood|first4=EH|title=Biplane videoangiography|journal=J Appl Physiol|date=May 1968|volume=24|number=5|pages=724\u2013727|pmid=5647655|doi=10.1152/jappl.1968.24.5.724}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sturm|first1=RE|last2=Wood|first2=EH|title=The video quantizer: an electronic photometer to measure contrast in roentgen fluoroscopic images|journal=Mayo Clin. Proc.|date=November 1968|volume=43|number=11|pages=803\u2013806|pmid=5711440}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Greenleaf|first1=JF|last2=Ritman|first2=EL|last3=Wood|first3=EH|last4=Robb|first4=RA|last5=Johnson|first5=SA|title=Dynamic computer-generated displays of data from biplane roentgen angiography for study of the left ventricle|journal=Ann. Biomed. Eng.|date=March 1974|volume=2|number=1|pages=90\u2013105|pmid=4596338|doi=10.1007/bf02368088}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=HC|last2=Sturm|first2=RE|last3=Wood|first3=EH|title=Videodensitometric system for measurement of vessel blood flow, particularly in the coronary arteries, in man|journal=Am J Cardiol|date=August 1973|volume=32|number=2|pages=144\u2013150|pmid=4578631|doi=10.1016/s0002-9149(73)80112-2}}</ref> and \n* the earliest predecessor (The Dynamic Spatial Reconstructor)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=EH|last2=Ritman|first2=EL|last3=Robb|first3=RA|last4=Harris|first4=LD|last5=Ruegsegger|first5=P|title=Noninvasive numerical vivisection of anatomic structure and function of the intact circulatory system using high temporal resolution cylindrical scanning computerized tomography|journal=Med. Instrum.|date=May 1977|volume=11|number=3|pages=153\u2013159|pmid=875764}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Johnson|first1=SA|last2=Robb|first2=RA|last3=Greenleaf|first3=JF|last4=Ritman|first4=EL|last5=Lee|first5=SL|last6=Herman|first6=GT|last7=Sturm|first7=RE|last8=Wood|first8=EH|title=The problem of accurate measurement of left ventricular shape and dimensions from multiplane roentgenographic data|journal=Eur J Cardiol.|date=March 1974|volume=1|number=3|pages=241\u2013258|pmid=4613557}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Wood|first=EH|title=The dream of a dynamic, high-fidelity, synchronous, volumetric imaging system and the road to its realization|journal=Herz|date=August 1985|volume=10|issue=4 |pages=183\u2013192|pmid=3899883}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ritman|first1=EL|last2=Robb|first2=RA|last3=Harris|first3=LD|title=Imaging Physiological Functions: Experience with the Dynamic Spatial Reconstructor|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=1985|isbn=0030693527}}</ref> of modern high speed, multi-source / multi-detector row computed tomography for the non-invasive imaging of the beating heart and breathing lungs.\n\nWood's publication list, with more than 700 entries, is a testament to the number of fellows who trained under him and who became prominent researchers in their own right.\n\n== Early life ==\nEarl Wood was born to Inez Goff and William Clark Wood in Mankato, Minnesota on January 1, 1912 and started life on a subsistence farm.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite AV media|title=Inventing the G-suit: The Life Story of Dr. Earl Wood|first1=Bill|last1=Bonde|first2=Karen|last2=Bonde|url=https://vimeo.com/1924164}}</ref>  William Wood, in addition to farming, was a real estate businessman. Earl Wood earned a B.A. in Mathematics and Chemistry from Macalester College in 1934, and his MD degree and a PhD degree in physiology from the University of Minnesota. Earl was one of 5 brothers (Earl, Chester, Delbert, Harland and Abe) and a sister, Louise.\n\n== Family ==\nAll of Earl Wood's siblings grew up to be highly accomplished.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Louise A. Wood was awarded the [[Medal of Freedom (1945)|Medal of Freedom]] by President Truman for her services as over-seas director of the American Red Cross during World War II. and became the executive director of the [[Girl Scouts of the USA]] from 1961-1972. [[Harland G. Wood]] was the first director of the Department of Biochemistry at the School of Medicine and Dean of Sciences, Case Western Reserve University. As a biochemist, he was notable for proving in 1935 that animals, humans and bacteria utilized carbon dioxide<ref>Wood HG, Utter MF. The role of CO2 fixation in metabolism. Essays Biochem. 1965;1:1-27. Review. PubMed {{PMID|4880809}}.</ref> and received the National Medal of Science. Chester was a teacher and a university administrator; Delbert was, in succession, a lawyer, a Federal Bureau of Investigation agent, and a railway executive; Abe was an internist and founder of a Colorado-based medical clinic. Not surprisingly, in 1950, Earl Wood's mother, Inez, was awarded the title of \"Minnesota Mother of the Year.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>  Earl and his wife, Ada, had a daughter, Phoebe and three sons, Mark, Guy and E. Andrew.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, Earl H.}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:American physiologists]]\n[[Category:American medical researchers]]\n[[Category:Cardiovascular researchers]]\n[[Category:American biomedical engineers]]\n"